Aside from wrapping my export routine in a WordPress friendly plugin, accurately transforming the URLs from my Community Server website has been the most time-consuming part of the Community Server to WordPress migration. A domain name change further complicated things, quickly devolving URL rewriting into a non-trivial endeavor.<br /><br />Keep in mind, however, that how you ultimately handle URL rewriting depends largely on where you are relocating to, and how you plan to get there. For example, if you've decided to make the switch to an Apache-based hosting solution, your options will be much different that moving to an IIS-based one.<br /><a name='more'></a><br />Because of some factors not directly related to the blog, I went down the shared-hosting-IIS road, which presented a set of unique challenges. In my case, I had some pretty particular requirements:<br /><ul><li>Rewrite old URLs in the most search engine friendly way possible.</li>
<li>Not break any existing external links.</li>
<li>Eliminate any lasting dependency on the Community Server database.</li>
<li>Implement truly "pretty" URLs, so that I don't ever have to go through this process again.</li>
<li>Continue to use shared hosting.</li>
<li>Avoid having to inspect every incoming request regardless of whether it needed to be rewritten or not.</li>
<li>Retain a single point of management for application hosting, regardless of the underlying technologies.</li>
</ul>All pretty standard fare, really. But the last point above created an aversion to using a LAMP-based hosting package. I needed the ability to run PHP and MS.NET on the same server, preferably side-by-side. IIS7, here we come.<br /><br />The next problem I ran into was the availability of a ready-made, pattern based URL rewriting tool. Apache's mod_rewrite module wasn't an option. IIS7, when finally released in RTM form, will include a native URL rewriter much like it, but because this is presently a CTP add-on most hosting providers haven't installed it yet. ISAPI-based solutions like ISAPI Rewrite or the <a href="http://www.codeplex.com/IIRF">freeware IIRF component</a> are also options, but it's rare to find these in a shared hosting environment, and IIRF isn't II7 ready anyhow.<br /><br />I finally realized that I was going to have write some code to get what I wanted. Taking some cues from Dave Bost's <a href="http://davebost.com/blog/2008/01/28/attempting-some-permalink-magic/">post on the subject</a>, here's the high-level approach I followed:<br /><br />First, I installed the <em><a href="http://www.nathanm.com/myprojects/#plugin">Remove index.php from Permalinks in IIS</a></em> plug-in to get rid of the "index.php" in my WordPress URLs. You may need to regenerate your permalinks in WordPress using the admin console before you get much further, since you'll need them to be production ready for the mapping process to work.<br /><br />Next I saved the output of the Google sitemap that is dynamically generated by Community Server as an XML document. In my case, this represented almost all of the URLs I had to worry about. If you're skilled in regex and/or SQL-XML, this file will come in <strong>very</strong> handy.<br /><br />At this point, I started poking around in the Community Server database, and realized something I hadn't paid much attention to before. Because I had upgraded through the years from DotText, the format of my links was inconsistent. Some used the pseudo-pretty Community Server format, while some were still in the ugly DotText format.<br /><br />After a bit of quick testing, I also discovered the method used to escape special characters in a URL is different in Community Server than it is in WordPress, and that Community Server allows multiple URL formats for the same content. Even though the latter probably wouldn't have a huge impact on SEO (since the alternate formats didn't appear in the sitemap output), I didn't want to risk breaking an external link somewhere. In the end, I decided to handle the following Community Server link formats, which meant three possible inbound matches for each WordPress post:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>&lt;!-- CS 2007 format --&gt;
<br />http://oldsite/archive/YYYY/mm/dd/some-intersting-post-title.aspx
<br />&lt;!-- some old CS format I think --&gt;
<br />http://oldsite/archive/YYYY/mm/dd/1446.aspx
<br />&lt;!-- legacy DotText format --&gt;
<br />http://oldsite/1234.aspx
<br /></code></pre>Once I had determined the link formats I was going to support, I grabbed the output from my <a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/google-sitemap-generator/">WordPress Google sitemap</a>. Again, you may need to regenerate this manually, since you're WordPress permalinks probably changed after installing the permalink plugin.<br /><br />After a few hours of some creative SQL-XML and regex work on the Community Server database, the Community Server sitemap, and the WordPress sitemap, I had an XML document that I could use to build an in-memory dictionary to map the old URLs. The schema looks something like this:<pre class="kccodeblock"><code>&lt;urls oldUrlRoot="http://kriscargile.com/" newUrlRoot="http://www.kristophercargile.com/"&gt;
<br />&lt;url sourceType="post"&gt;
<br />&lt;new&gt;2008/06/29/atlanta-scrum-users-group-formed/&lt;/new&gt;
<br />&lt;old&gt;archive/2008/06/29/atlanta-scrum-user-group-formed.aspx&lt;/old&gt;
<br />&lt;/url&gt;
<br />&lt;/urls&gt;
<br /></code></pre>I decided to represent the old and new root paths as attributes, since this greatly simplified local testing, and allowed me to use the newUrlRoot value as a fallback for an invalid or deleted URL.<br /><br />Using the Application_Start event handler in Global.asax, the XML file is parsed into a cached Hashtable. A cache dependency on the XML file allows for easy tweaks without the need to bounce IIS. Each inbound request is then handled by Application_BeginRequest&mdash;which handles <em>every</em> client request and fires at the start of the ASP.NET pipeline&mdash;to see if the old URL exists in the hashtable, and where the subsequent 301 should point to.<br /><br />Finally, I replaced the old Community Server website with the new Global.asax file. Once everything was tested and verified, I backed up my old Community Server database and dropped it.<br /><br />The source code for the rewriter is below. You'll need to generate your own content for the XML mapping file, though a stub is included.<br /><br />If you decide to use or extend it, I'd appreciate your feedback.<br /><br />klc;<br /><br /><a href='http://cdn.kriscargile.com/samples/cs2wp-url-reqwriter.zip'>cs2wp-url-rewriter.zip</a>

Though not particularly sexy, parsing a delimited string is a pretty common programming task. And while it's not difficult to build a couple of simple functions to slice and dice this type of data, you often find yourself duplicating this functionality to accommodate multiple return types. Add to this the fact that .NET doesn't support overloading by return type only, and you'll eventually end up with a mess of nearly identical, yet seemingly disconnected logic.<br /><br />Wouldn't it be nice if you could just write one function that would automatically process your string, and return a list of objects typed exactly how you want? Thanks to generics, you can.<br /><a name='more'></a><br />For example, take the following, comma-delimited string of integers:<br /><blockquote><span style="font-family: Courier New;">"1,2,3,5,8,13"</span></blockquote>To deserialize our Fibonacci sequence we could create a function that uses the <span style="font-family: Courier New;">String.Split</span> method to iterate through the results, cast each of the objects to an <span style="font-family: Courier New;">Int32</span>, and then return a new integer array. Something like this:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>public static int[] Deserialize(string vals)
<br />{
<br />  string[] tempList = vals.Split(‘,’);
<br />  int[] listWeWant = new int[tempList.Length];
<br />
<br />  // iterate and cast; this is a O(n) operation
<br />  for (int i = 0; i &lt; listWeWant.Length; i++)
<br />  {
<br />    // assumes the original string contains only ints
<br />    listWeWant[i] = int.Parse(tempList[i]);
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  return listWeWant;
<br />}</code></pre>This approach is pretty commonplace, and it works just fine if all of your delimited strings contain only integers. But by wrapping this functionality inside your own constrained generic function, you can provide your application with a common way to parse delimited strings containing almost any primitive data type.<br /><br />So, our new parsing function will look something like this:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>public static T[] Deserialize(string vals, char delim)
<br />where T : class, IConvertible
<br />{
<br />  string[] sList = vals.Split(delim);
<br />
<br />  // also a O(n) operation
<br />  T[] arr = (T[])Array.CreateInstance(typeof(T), sList.Length);
<br />
<br />  for (int i = 0; i &lt; sList.Length; i++)
<br />  {
<br />    Type toft = typeof(T);
<br />    arr[i] = sList[i] as T;
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  return arr;
<br />}</code></pre>The generic type parameter <span style="font-family: Courier New;">T</span> allows you to ask for an array of a specific type when calling <span style="font-family: Courier New;">Deserialize</span>. If your string contains integers, you'll get back an <span style="font-family: Courier New;">int[]</span>, doubles a <span style="font-family: Courier New;">double[]</span>, and so on. The only limitation imposed is that the type specified in the type parameter <span style="font-family: Courier New;">T</span> must implement the <span style="font-family: Courier New;">IConvertible</span> interface. This limitation is explicitly defined in the constraint clause at the end of the method signature (the <span style="font-family: Courier New;">where T : class, IConvertible</span> statement.) This constraint tells the compiler to require <span style="font-family: Courier New;">T</span> to be a class that implements <span style="font-family: Courier New;">IConvertible</span>, which provides a bit of type checking for the function and prevents us from passing in an object that our code can't convert.<br /><br />Note that while this approach should be adequate for most needs, you could conceivably modify complex types to work here by implementing <span style="font-family: Courier New;">IConvertible </span>(though you might want to consider XML serialization instead for those cases.)<br /><br />Also keep in mind that this still a linear operation -- O(<em>n</em>) where <em>n</em> is the number of elements in your array. If you are working with very large sets of data the performance hit could be substantial, and you'd be wise to investigate more efficient ways of processing and/or persisting your data.<br /><br /><a href="http://cdn.kriscargile.com/samples/arrayutil.zip">arrayutil.zip</a><br /><br />klc;<br />

If you've used Microsoft's Enterprise Library very much, then you've probably noticed how nicely the configuration files seem to come together. Despite being incredibly complex at times, these are often akin to the .NET provider model configuration, where entire configuration nodes are pluggable with previously unknown configuration types. The EL does this by allowing you to specify two types for these types of nodes via XML attributes -- one for the configuration element's concrete type, and one for the actual type of object you are setting up.<br /><a name='more'></a><br />Here's an example of what I'm talking about, taken directly from a MSEL configuration file (incidentally, this one is from the logging application block's <span style="font-family: Courier New;">&lt;loggingConfiguration&gt;</span> section):<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>&lt;listeners&gt;
<br />&lt;add
<br />fileName="c:\apptrace.log"
<br />header="##"
<br />footer="##"
<br />formatter="Text Formatter"
<br />traceOutputOptions="None"
<br />name="FlatFile TraceListener"
<br />listenerDataType="Microsoft.Practices.EnterpriseLibrary.Logging.Configuration.EmailTraceListenerData, Microsoft.Practices.EnterpriseLibrary.Logging, Version=2.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null"
<br />type="Microsoft.Practices.EnterpriseLibrary.Logging.TraceListeners.EmailTraceListener, Microsoft.Practices.EnterpriseLibrary.Logging, Version=2.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null"
<br />/&gt;
<br />&lt;/listeners&gt;</code></pre>If you're not totally familiar with what this piece of XML does, don't worry. The important things to notice are that the listener is added using a few special properties: first, the <span style="font-family: Courier New;">add</span> attribute instructs the configuration subsystem to add the new listener to the corresponding listeners collection, while <span style="font-family: Courier New;">listenerDataType</span> and <span style="font-family: Courier New;">type</span> tell it how to create the configuration and listener objects the block should use. Internally, the MSEL builds these at runtime using reflection, allowing you to create new listener types and add them on-the-fly, all without modifying the core configuration logic.<br /><br />The .NET Framework has built in support for early-bound, strongly-typed and late-bound, weakly-typed configuration elements via the <span style="font-family: Courier New;">System.Configuration</span> namespace. You've probably used these, even if only passively -- Web.Config and App.Config are chock full of them.<br /><br />But what happens when you want to create a custom configuration format that is fully extensible and can scale with your application? You can use the Framework's built in types to handle all of this, but then each time you add a new type, you'll have to modify the underlying configuration classes to support it. This becomes even more difficult if you have factories that hand-out these types polymorphically.<br /><br />Luckily, the same infrastructure used internally by the MSEL is exposed publicly (and very well documented, I might add) via the <span style="font-family: Courier New;">Microsoft.Practices.Common.Configuration</span> namespace. There are two types that are of particular interest in this situation: <span style="font-family: Courier New;">NamedConfigurationElement</span>, which is a <span style="font-family: Courier New;">ConfiugurationElement</span> object that is keyed by its name (using the <span style="font-family: Courier New;">name</span> attribute from the config file); and the <span style="font-family: Courier New;">PolymorphicConfigurationElementCollection</span>, which is a templated collection class to hold these objects. The beauty of the <span style="font-family: Courier New;">NamedConfigurationElement</span> class, is that it instantiates your custom configuration object automatically at runtime using the type name provided in the configuration. All you need to do is build the objects that will represent and use your custom configuration.<br /><br />Say, for example, that we're building a task service. This service will initially manage some files and then send an email when its finished. Since we may need the service to carry out additional tasks in the future, we'll need to keep things as flexible as possible.<br /><br />Take for instance, the following configuration file snippet:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>&lt;taskman&gt;
<br />&lt;jobs&gt;
<br />&lt;job id="13D23CB5-139E-4594-92DB-3556DC889CFD"&gt;
<br />&lt;tasks&gt;
<br />&lt;add
<br />name="compressionTask"
<br />taskDataType="bettersoftwarenow.samples.TaskMan.Configuration.CompressTaskElement,bettersoftwarenow.samples.TaskMan"
<br />type="bettersoftwarenow.samples.TaskMan.CompressTask,bettersoftwarenow.samples.TaskMan"
<br />algorithm="Zip"
<br />sourcePath="c:\files"
<br />outputPath="c:\files_backup"
<br />notifyOnComplete="True"
<br />filterPattern="\.log"
<br />recurse="True"
<br />/&gt;
<br />&lt;/tasks&gt;
<br />&lt;notificationlisteners&gt;
<br />&lt;add
<br />name="emailListener"
<br />listenerDataType="bettersoftwarenow.samples.TaskMan.Configuration.EmailNotificationListenerElement,bettersoftwarenow.samples.TaskMan"
<br />type="bettersoftwarenow.samples.TaskMan.EmailNotificationListener,bettersoftwarenow.samples.TaskMan"
<br />toAddress="noone@domain.com"
<br />fromAddress="system@domain.com"
<br />smtpServer="localhost"
<br />smtpPort="25" /&gt;
<br />&lt;/notificationListeners&gt;
<br />&lt;/job&gt;
<br />&lt;/jobs&gt;
<br />&lt;/taskMan&gt;</code></pre>As you may have guessed, this application will zip up some files and send an email when it's finished. Using a polymorphic configuration architecture will allow us to add additional tasks in the future very easily, say shipping the output via FTP or sending an SMS message.<br /><br />Several classes will be required to handle configuration of the application. I'll defer the implementation of most of these to the reader, but the examples below outline how you can use the MSEL classes to get things started (for brevity's sake, I've omitted things like validators and some of the more esoteric configuration attributes -- I'd strongly recommend that you look into these carefully, however, as you'll want to make your configuration as iron-clad as possibile):<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>// utilizes a polymorphic child element
<br />public class JobElement : ConfigurationElement
<br />{
<br />  [ConfigurationProperty("id", IsKey = true)]
<br />  public string Id
<br />  {
<br />    get { return Convert.ToString(this["id"]); }
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  [ConfigurationProperty("tasks", IsDefaultCollection = false)]
<br />  [ConfigurationCollection(typeof(TaskElementCollection))]
<br />  public TaskElementCollection Tasks
<br />  {
<br />    get { return (TaskElementCollection)this["tasks"]; }
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  // property for the parent config node
<br />  [ConfigurationProperty("notificationListeners", IsDefaultCollection = false)]
<br />  [ConfigurationCollection(typeof(NotificationListenerElementCollection))]
<br />  public NotificationListenerElementCollection Listeners
<br />  {
<br />    get
<br />    {
<br />      return (NotificationListenerElementCollection)
<br />      this["notificationListeners"];
<br />    }
<br />  }
<br />  // other config properties omitted
<br />}
<br />
<br />// base class for notification config elements
<br />public class NotificationListenerElementBase : NamedConfigurationElement
<br />{
<br />  // name of the property that holds the type for our base
<br />  protected internal const string listenerDataTypeProperty = "listenerDataType”;
<br />
<br />  // concrete type for our config element
<br />  [ConfigurationProperty(listenerDataTypeProperty, IsRequired = true)]
<br />  [TypeConverter(typeof(AssemblyQualifiedTypeNameConverter))]
<br />  public Type ListenerDataType
<br />  {
<br />    get { return (Type)this[listenerDataTypeProperty]; }
<br />    set { this[listenerDataTypeProperty] = value; }
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  // concrete type attribute for our notification objects
<br />  [ConfigurationProperty("type", IsRequired = true)]
<br />  [TypeConverter(typeof(AssemblyQualifiedTypeNameConverter))]
<br />  public Type ListenerType
<br />  {
<br />    get { return (Type)this["type"]; }
<br />    set { this["type"] = value; }
<br />  }
<br />}
<br />
<br />// polymorphic collection for notification config elements
<br />public class NotificationListenerElementCollection : PolymorphicConfigurationElementCollection<notificationlistenerelementbase>
<br />{
<br />  protected override Type RetrieveConfigurationElementType(XmlReader reader)
<br />  {
<br />    // implementation omitted
<br />    return null;
<br />  }
<br />}
<br />
<br />// concrete example that matches the config
<br />public class EmailNotificationListenerElement : NotificationListenerElementBase
<br />{
<br />  [ConfigurationProperty("toAddress")]
<br />  public string ToAddress
<br />  {
<br />    get { return Convert.ToString(this["toAddress"]); }
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  [ConfigurationProperty("fromAddress")]
<br />  public string FromAddress
<br />  {
<br />    get { return Convert.ToString(this["fromAddress"]); }
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  [ConfigurationProperty("smtpServer")]
<br />  public string SmtpServer
<br />  {
<br />    get { return Convert.ToString(this["smtpServer"]); }
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  [ConfigurationProperty("smtpPort")]
<br />  public int SmtpPort
<br />  {
<br />    get { return Convert.ToInt32(this["smtpPort"]); }
<br />  }
<br />}
<br />
<br />// config element class that utilizes a polymorphic child element
<br />public class JobElement : ConfigurationElement
<br />{
<br />  [ConfigurationProperty("id", IsKey = true)]
<br />  public string Id
<br />  {
<br />    get { return Convert.ToString(this["id"]); }
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  [ConfigurationProperty("tasks", IsDefaultCollection = false)]
<br />  [ConfigurationCollection(typeof(TaskElementCollection))]
<br />  public TaskElementCollection Tasks
<br />  {
<br />    get { return (TaskElementCollection)this["tasks"]; }
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  // property for the parent config node - this is
<br />  // where the notification config items will be instantiated
<br />  [ConfigurationProperty("notificationListeners", IsDefaultCollection = false)]
<br />  [ConfigurationCollection(typeof(NotificationListenerElementCollection))]
<br />  public NotificationListenerElementCollection Listeners
<br />  {
<br />    get
<br />    {
<br />      return (NotificationListenerElementCollection)
<br />	    this["notificationListeners"];
<br />    }
<br />  }
<br />  // other config properties omitted
<br />}</code></pre>Essentially, these classes will allow you to parse the <span style="font-family: Courier New;">&lt;job&gt;</span> configuration element and instantiate configuration classes for the listeners you've configured. It doesn't matter what type these items are, provided that the configuration element contains the <span style="font-family: Courier New;">type</span> and <span style="font-family: Courier New;">listenerDataType</span> attributes (and if it doesn't, you'll get an error). Note that you'll need to add your own classes to support the tasks themselves, otherwise you'll get an exception when the <span style="font-family: Courier New;">ConfigurationManager</span> encounters the <span style="font-family: Courier New;">&lt;tasks&gt;</span> node.<br /><br />Finally, to use the objects that you've configured polymorphically, you'll instantiate them with reflection using the type information read from the configuration file:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>// this interface will allow us to easily invoke members
<br />// on our polymorphic notification objects at runtime
<br />public interface IJobItem
<br />{
<br />  bool Execute();
<br />}
<br />
<br />// a concrete notification task
<br />public class EmailNotificationListener : IJobItem
<br />{
<br />  internal EmailNotificationListener(EmailNotificationListenerElement config)
<br />  {
<br />    // configure the class
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  public int Execute(EventArgs args)
<br />  {
<br />    // send your notifications
<br />    return 0;
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  public bool Execute()
<br />  {
<br />    // execute the task
<br />    return false;
<br />  }
<br />}
<br />
<br />// a concrete notification task
<br />public class Job
<br />{
<br />  // collection for our concrete notification objects
<br />  private IJobItemAsyncCollection _listeners = new IJobItemAsyncCollection();
<br />
<br />  // delegate to handle execution
<br />  private delegate int NotificationDel(JobCompleteEventArgs args);
<br />
<br />  // we’ll mutlicast to fire our objects
<br />  private NotificationDel ntfyMulti = null;
<br />
<br />  // event that fires when our job is finished
<br />  public event JobCompleteEventHandler JobComplete;
<br />
<br />  internal Job(JobElement config)
<br />  {
<br />    JobComplete += new JobCompleteEventHandler(Job_JobComplete);
<br />    SetupListeners(config.Listeners);
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  // news up our listeners using reflection and
<br />  // adds them to the multi-cast delegate
<br />  private void SetupListeners(NotificationListenerElementCollection listeners)
<br />  {
<br />    Type listenerType = null;
<br />    foreach (NotificationListenerElementBase span> neb in listeners)
<br />    {
<br />      listenerType = neb.ListenerType;
<br />
<br />      // use reflection to create our concrete objects
<br />      ConstructorInfo c = listenerType.GetConstructor(
<br />      BindingFlags.Instance | BindingFlags.NonPublic,
<br />        null, new Type[] { neb.GetType() }, null);
<br />
<br />      IJobItemAsync listenerObj = (IJobItemAsync)c.Invoke(new object[] { neb });
<br />      ntfyMulti += listenerObj.Execute;
<br />
<br />      _listeners.Add(listenerObj);
<br />    }
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  // fires the multi-cast delegate when called
<br />  private void Job_JobComplete(object sender, JobCompleteEventArgs e)
<br />  {
<br />    ntfyMulti.Invoke(e);
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  // remaining implementation omitted
<br />}</code></pre>Any way you look at it, it takes a lot of code to implement a full-featured custom configuration schema. But doing so can be highly valuable to your customers and is incredibly powerful. Using the MSEL simplifies much of the plumbing, saving you lots of time and probably frustration -- all while ensuring that your application can easily grow.<br /><br />The attached sample contains a (mostly) working ZIP compression tool.<br /><br />Happy configuring!<br /><br /><a href="http://cdn.kriscargile.com/samples/polymorphic-msel.zip">polymorphic-msel.zip</a><br /><br />klc;

A while back, I blogged about using alternate configuration contexts with the MSEL 1.1. It turns out that even with the improved configuration capabilities of .NET 2.0, using the MSEL in a loosely coupled, n-tier environment will also require you to jump through some hoops.<br /><br />The primary reason for this is that the .NET CLR only gives you one configuration context per AppDomain (<a href="http://blogs.msdn.com/suzcook/" target="_blank">Suzanne Cook</a> has some great info on her website about this). A stand-alone business logic layer therefore would have configuration context equivalent to Web.config if you're using it in an ASP.NET application, thus rendering your app.config file invisible.<br /><a name='more'></a><br />Ultimately, you have two options. You can put the MSEL configuration data directly in Web.config, but this severely limits the scalability and reusability of your application. The better alternative is to use the MSEL factories that are designed specifically for this purpose.<br /><br />The way that you go about this is similar to it was in the 1.1 version of the MSEL, with a couple of key differences. First, you'll need an instance of a class that implements the IConfiurationSource interface to get a handle to the configuration file. IConfigurationSource is new in MSEL 2.0, and it allows you to explicitly define your configuration source (as in our case) or to use a non-standard names, formats, etc. (an RDB, for example). You'll use this instance as an argument for the factory methods for each of the blocks.<br /><br />The most common of the IConfigurationSource implementers is FileConfigurationSource which, incidentally, is the default used internally by the MSEL. I typically create an internal static instance of this, so that all of my classes can share a common configuration instance. For example:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>private static IConfigurationSource cfgSource = new FileConfigurationSource("MyConfigFileName.dll.config");</code></pre>Be careful, however, if you're building an API that could be used by a variety of hosting processes. Since you don't want to make any assumptions about the location of the config file relative to the hosting application, you're a little safer determining it at runtime. We'll modify the code above slightly to reflect this:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>private static string ConfigFileName = Path.GetDirectoryName(Assembly.GetExecutingAssembly().CodeBase).Replace(@”file:\”, “”) + “\\” + "MyAssembly.dll.config";
<br />private static IConfigurationSource cfgSource = new FileConfigurationSource(ConfigFileName);</code></pre>Now you only need to get an instance of each block using the alternate IConfigurationSource. Again, I typically put these in a location common to my assembly. One word of caution: you may be tempted to put these somewhere common to your application and make them public, but this will represent a risk to your application. Users of your API could easily throw a wrench in your exception handling aspect or could subvert the isolation to data access provided by your BLL. It also potentially increases coupling between assmeblies. If you choose to do this, use ILDASM and ILASM to change the protection level of these members to something more appropriate like <span style="font-family: courier;">famorassm</span>.<br /><br />Either way, you'll end up with declarations like the following:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>private static IConfigurationSource cfgSource = new FileConfigurationSource(ConfigFileName);
<br />internal static CacheManagerFactory CacheFactory = new CacheManagerFactory(cfgSource);
<br />internal static ExceptionPolicyFactory ExceptionFactory = new ExceptionPolicyFactory(cfgSource);
<br />internal static DatabaseProviderFactory DataFactory = new DatabaseProviderFactory(cfgSource);</code></pre>You'll then use these members to access the MSEL instead of the typical public methods. For the most part they'll work the same, though the arguments are usually arranged a little differently. For example, an exception is passed to the ExceptionHandling block as follows:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>try
<br />{
<br />  // TODO: do something useful..
<br />}
<br />catch(Exception e)
<br />{
<br />  bool rethrow = ExceptionFactory.Create(“Data”).HandleException(e);
<br />}</code></pre>A little extra time in planning your MSEL implementation will save you hours and hours of development time, and will help your application to scale without abandon.<br /><br />Happy factoring!<br /><br /><a href="http://cdn.kriscargile.com/samples/ntier-msel.zip">ntier-msel.zip</a><br /><br />klc;

If you've been lucky enough to do any development using .NET 2.0 and the CTP of the Enterprise Library 2.0 then you've likely noticed the absence of the Configuration Application Block in the new EL, as well as the new and improved configuration functionality built into the framework. In .NET 2.0 you are not limited to executable projects for built-in access to configuration data via App.Config (or Web.config for that matter).<br /><a name='more'></a><br />But if you're still developing using .NET 1.1 and the 1.1 release of the EL and you're building reusable class libraries, then you'll probably want to carry some configuration data around with your assemblies. In this case, storing your configuration information in the hosting process' config file, say Web.config, couples your assembly to the UI and thus undermines portability. Luckily, the Enterprise Library allows you to create custom configuration contexts for just this purpose.<br /><br />You can defined your custom configuration in a few simple steps:<br /><br />1) Define your custom configuration file. For my class libraries, I usually call this App.config for the sake of familiarity. The format of this file is basic XML as with any other .NET configuration file.<br /><br />2) Since the class library won't automatically create the properly named version of the config file, you'll need a post-build event to rename the file and move it to the correct place. You could also just name the file this way to begin with, but I personally like to have my config files in \bin and I generally prefer not to check items in \bin into source control. In any event, my post-build script contains something like this:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>copy "..\..\Configuration\App.config" ".\MyNamespace.MyApp.dll.config"</code></pre>3) Now you simply need to get a reference to the new config file at runtime. I typically put this somewhere global (but internal) to my application so that its easily accessible. For example:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>private const string AppConfigFileName = "MyNamespace.MyApp.dll.config";
<br />private static ConfigurationContext _cfgCtx = null;
<br />
<br />internal static ConfigurationContext ConfigContext
<br />{
<br />  get
<br />  {
<br />    if (_cfgCtx == null)
<br />    {
<br />      string assmCodeBase = Assembly.GetExecutingAssembly().CodeBase;
<br />      string assmPath = assmCodeBase.Remove(0, 8);
<br />      assmPath = assmPath.Substring(0, assmPath.LastIndexOf('/'));
<br />      string configPath = assmPath + "/" + AppConfigFileName;
<br />
<br />      _cfgCtx = ConfigurationManager.CreateContext(configPath);
<br />    }
<br />
<br />    return _cfgCtx;
<br />  }
<br />}</code></pre>One of the great, relatively unknown features of the Enterprise Library is that each of the Application Block factories will let you pass in a custom configuration context in as an argument exactly for this purpose. So now when you need to, say, handle an exception, you instantiate the ExceptionPolicy like so:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>bool rethrow = ExceptionPolicy.HandleException(e, "Data", ConfigContext);</code></pre>And that's all it takes. Each of the other blocks works in much the same way, allowing you to instrument your reusable assemblies independently of one another and independent from whatever process might be hosting them.<br /><br /><a href="http://cdn.kriscargile.com/samples/custommselconfig.zip">custommselconfig.zip</a><br /><br />klc;

After spending a better part of the day yesterday pulling my hair out unit testing some operator overloads, I and a colleague discovered a subtle difference between .NETs intrinsic DateTime implementation and SQL Server's DateTime data type that Id never run across  the differences in precision were causing all of my comparisons to fail.<br /><br />The intrinsic .NET DateTime object is a simple value type (a struct), and is contained in mscorlib.dll. Its implementation is fairly simple:  the value is measured as the number of ticks that have passed since January 01, 0001. A tick, in case you were wondering, is a 100 nanoseconds (that's 100 * 10^-9, or 0.0000001 seconds).<br /><a name='more'></a><br />DateTimes in SQL Server are represented a little differently, however. The DateTime type Transact-Sql has a precision of one three hundredths of a second (thats 0.00333 seconds). Use a small date time and the grain gets even bigger, growing all the way to 1 second.<br /><br />Clearly, .NETs DateTime data type is more precise than SQL's. Since humans cant really comprehend the magnitude of 1 billionth of a second, you may be asking yourself, why should I care? In a word, comparisons.<br /><br />Since shuttling a DateTime back-and-forth between SQL Server causes the base time value to change (from what appears to be because of internal rounding; quick testing shows the delta is usually less than 20,000 ticks), the DateTime implementation of Equals and ==  will always fail. A quick look at System.DateTime with Reflector verifies that both of these operations look only at the ticks:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>public override bool Equals(object value)
<br />{
<br />  if (value is DateTime)
<br />  {
<br />    time1 = (DateTime)value;
<br />    return (this.ticks == time1.ticks);
<br />  }
<br />  return false;
<br />}
<br />
<br />public static bool operator ==(DateTime d1, DateTime d2)
<br />{
<br />  return (d1.ticks == d2.ticks);
<br />}
<br /></code></pre>You could use the SqlDateTime object in your business objects to represent DateTime values, but this tightly couples your business objects to the underlying data store  something you should generally try to avoid.<br /><br />In our case, the solution was to build a simple comparison function that compares the requisite DateTime components individually without respect to ticks return the collective result. Keep in mind that, in instances where precision down to hundredths of a second is important, this wont work. But for your typical business application, this approach seems to fit the bill.<br /><br /><a href="http://cdn.kriscargile.com/samples/somedataobject.zip">somedataobject.zip</a><br /><br />klc;

If you are developing using .NET for Windows XP SP2 or Windows 2003 Server, one of the cooler features you can take advantage of is the support for COM+ transactions via the Transaction Internet Protocol.<br /><br />Transaction Internet Protocol, or TIP, is a MSDTC feature that allows (among other things) .NET assemblies to request COM+ transaction services at runtime. This really amounts to dynamically entering your component into an Enterprise Services context, starting (or joining) a transaction, then exiting from the Enterprise Services context to go about your business.<br /><a name='more'></a><br />There are some real obvious advantages to using transactions in this way, not the least of which is that you get all of the advantages of a COM+ transaction without building a full-blown serviced component  not a trivial consideration in light of .NETs single implementation inheritance.<br /><br />Transactions have always been a great way to supplement TDD. For MS.Net TIP fits the bill, and can be used to easily prevent leaving behind evidence of your tests. Lets say, for example, that I need to write a fixture that tests a user registration class. Assume that as part of the standard registration process well do a few database inserts and send an email to the user confirming his registration. If any one of these operations fail I want to rollback database changes, and Id also like to avoid sending a user an invalid welcome email.<br /><br />Of course, you could implement this fairly trivial example using basic conditional logic. But in a large, complex system this approach almost always yields complex, hard-to-follow algorithms. Again, you could replace these with a pattern like strategy, but why bother when enterprise services has already done all of the tedious work?<br /><br />If you've not used TIP before, you'll need to enable it in your environment. Windows 2003 does not install network DTC support automatically, so you'll need to run through a few simple configuration steps before you can start testing (there are several good KB articles on MSDN and TechNet on how to do this; search for network DTC TIP).<br /><br />Keep in mind that you'll need network DTC installed and TIP enabled on every server that will be involved in a transaction. This means that DTC must be setup on the database server, web servers, email servers, etc. DTC also has some specific port requirements, so you may need to loosen port restrictions in your production environment.<br /><br />Once you've got the configuration nailed down, the rest is easy. Here's our sample NUnit registration test fixture that uses a TIP transaction to rollback changes:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>[TestFixture]
<br />public class SampleTIPTestFixture
<br />{
<br />  [TestFixtureSetUp]
<br />  public void Init()
<br />  {
<br />    // using a TIP transaction
<br />    ServiceConfig mComCtx = new ServiceConfig();
<br />    mComCtx.Transaction = TransactionOption.Required;
<br />    ServiceDomain.Enter(mComCtx);
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  [TestFixtureTearDown]
<br />  public void CleanUp()
<br />  {
<br />    // will cause ALL tests to rollback
<br />    ContextUtil.SetAbort();
<br />
<br />    // exit the transaction
<br />    ServiceDomain.Leave();
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  [Test]
<br />  public void MyTransactionalTest()
<br />  {
<br />    bool regResult = false;
<br />
<br />    // do database inserts, send emails, etc.
<br />    // see if calls were successful
<br />
<br />    Assert.IsTrue(regResult);
<br />  }
<br />}</code></pre><br />Happy testing!<br /><br /><a href="http://cdn.kriscargie.com/samples/sampletiptestfixture.zip">sampletiptestfixture.zip</a><br /><br />klc;

Given even the simplest of deployment situations, proper versioning of a web application becomes critical to maintaining the application once in production. This is especially true when working with an application that's deployed in more than one release.<br /><br /><span>Luckily, <a href="http://ccnet.thoughtworks.com/" target="_blank">CruiseControl.NET</a> and <a href="http://nant.sourceforge.net/" target="_blank">NAnt</a> excel in these situations. The <a href="http://ccnet.thoughtworks.com/" target="_blank">CruiseControl</a> build number is automatically made available to <a href="http://nant.sourceforge.net/" target="_blank">NAnt</a> via the </span><span>${label-to-apply}</span><span> property, and can easily be appended to the version number in AssemblyInfo.cs using the <a href="http://nant.sourceforge.net/" target="_blank">NAnt</a> </span><span>replacetokens</span><span> filter task. But in an isolated development model, users might not be building the solution locally using <a href="http://nant.sourceforge.net/" target="_blank">NAnt</a>, so you cant always rely on this method. </span><br /><a name='more'></a><br /><span>Instead, you can use <a href="http://nant.sourceforge.net/" target="_blank">NAnt</a> to create a completely new AssemblyInfo.cs file at integration time. This leaves AssemblyInfo.cs untouched and buildable locally, while still allowing for great flexibility during the integration build. You can handle this by creating a new <a href="http://nant.sourceforge.net/">NAnt</a> </span><span>for versioning in each .build file:</span><br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>&lt;target name="version"&gt;
