<br />&lt;attribute value="My Product" type="AssemblyProductAttribute" /&gt;
<br />&lt;attribute value="(C) Your name here" type="AssemblyCopyrightAttribute" /&gt;
<br />&lt;/attributes&gt;
<br />&lt;references&gt;
<br />&lt;include name="System.EnterpriseServices.dll" /&gt;
<br />&lt;/references&gt;
<br />&lt;/asminfo&gt;
<br />&lt;/target&gt;</code></pre><br /><span>This target can then be called just before the <span style="color: blue;">&lt;</span><span style="color: #a31515;">csc</span><span style="color: blue;">&gt;</span> </span><span>task executes, and will replace the contents of the projects AssemblyInfo.cs file for the integration.</span><br /><br /><a href="http://cdn.kriscargile.com/samples/nant-snippet.zip">nant-snippet.zip</a><br /><br />klc;

If you've had the opportunity to build a localized application, chances are you've built a resource assembly to support localization efforts. But in a large, highly partitioned solution, deciding exactly where to store your resources is somewhat of a conundrum. Either you end up with twice as many projects in your solution, or you have a single resource assembly supporting your entire application.<br /><br />Of course, neither of these situations is ideal. You're either stuck with a solution that rapidly becomes so large that its unmanageable, or you've coupled your framework and business logic to a single resource assembly  a proposition that means your resource assembly doesn't reflect the segmentation in your assembly. Add to that the fact that very few large applications are ever static, and youve got a real challenge on your hands.<br /><a name='more'></a><br />And there are ways other than localization that resource assemblies can benefit your application. For the past two months, Ive been part of a team tasked with refactoring a mission-critical, core application for a rapidly growing startup. The business model of is changing on a daily basis, and weve quickly recognized that responding this change will be fundamental to the success of our project.<br /><br />For example, one of the ways that were using resource assemblies is as a unit of versioning for our data access layer. By storing the names of stored procedures in the resource assembly, we can more easily version our database in response to changes in the business or the underlying data model. And we've already accommodated most future localization needs, despite the fact that they've yet to be specified.<br /><br />The key to implementing this for us has been <a href="http://projectdistributor.readify.net/Releases/Release.aspx?releaseId=9" target="_blank">Readify's String Resource Generator</a> (SRG). The SRG is a command-line utility that can be configured to automatically generate a resource class for your assembly using a simple source text file. You can have Visual Studio execute the SRG as part of your build process, or you can call it from an automated build tool like NAnt.<br /><br />The documentation included with SRG is somewhat limited, left mostly to the sample solutions and readme files. But is usage is straight forward. For example, an SR.strings used to version stored procedures for an assembly might look something like this (comments have been removed for brevity):<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>#! accessor_class_accessibility = public
<br />#! culture_info = Resources.CultureInfo
<br />#! generate_class = false
<br />#! resource_namespace = kriscargile.com.examples.resources
<br />
<br />[strings]
<br />; Stored Procedure Names
<br />AccountSelectStoredProcedure = "spCOAccountSelById"
<br />AccountSelectBySalesRepStoredProcedure = "spCOAccountSelByRep"
<br />AccountSelectByIndustryStoredProcedure = "spCOAccountSelByIndustry"
<br />AccountDeleteStoredProcedure = "spCOAccountDel"
<br />AccountUpdateStoredProcedure = "spCOAccountUpd"
<br />AccountAddStoredProcedure = "spCOAccountUpd"</code></pre><br />Were using the Microsoft string resource format (take a close look at the source for the Enterprise Library projects), so our SR.strings entries can be accessed at design time using simple dot syntax. So, getting the name of the stored procedure used to select accounts would look something like:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>SR.AccontSelectStoredProcedure</code></pre><br />That's it. The SRG tool does most of the heavy lifting at compile time (were using NAnt and CruiseControl to automate our builds, most of the build file is omitted):<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>&lt;if test="${file::exists('SR.strings')}"&gt;
<br />&lt;attrib readonly="false" file=“SR.cs“ /&gt;
<br />&lt;attrib readonly="false" file=“SR.resx“ /&gt;
<br />&lt;exec program="SRGenerator"&gt;
<br />&lt;arg value="cs" /&gt;
<br />&lt;arg value="${project.name}" /&gt;
<br />&lt;arg value="SR.strings" /&gt;
<br />&lt;/exec&gt;
<br />&lt;/if&gt;
<br /></code></pre><br />The real key here is the NAnt tag that calls SRGenerator.exe. Now changes to text in our application, additional localization requirements, or changes to our data model require only a quick edit and recompile of the SR.strings text file for the calling assembly.<br /><br /><a href="http://cdn.kriscargile.com/samples/sr.zip">SR.zip</a><br /><br />klc;

I'm a big fan of simplicity. I'm also a big fan of high-quality, high-performance, and scalability. And if you are developing enterprise-scale software using MS.NET you can gain a leg-up in all of these fronts by taking advantage of <a href="http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/default.asp?url=/library/en-us/dnpag2/html/entlib.asp">Microsoft's Enterprise Library</a> (EL). The EL, which was developed by the well-respected Patterns and Practices team at Microsoft, rolls together and updates Microsoft's original Application Blocks into a common, extensible, scalable MS.NET API.<br /><a name='more'></a><br />If you're not familiar with the Enterprise Library or Application Blocks, they provide reusable chunks of code to help you more easily tackle mundane tasks like logging, exception handling, caching, and cryptography - all the while adhering to best-practice and providing you with liberal opportunity to exploit extensibility. The EL also does a great job of demonstrating another worthy topic: <a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0201633612/002-9528570-7737624">design patterns</a>. It's chock full of facades and factories, and even if you have no use for the functionality in the EL, you could do much worse than to look to it as a best-practice model or learning tool. Best of all, its available for free from Microsoft.<br /><br />How you choose to implement the EL will depend largely on your needs, and in how comfortable coupling to the EL. My usual practice - though my experience with the EL has been very positive - is to wrap the EL's functionality into my own facade classes. That way, major changes to the EL or requirements make replacing underlying functionality relatively transparent to higher layers in the application (as they should be).<br /><br />For example, invoking the EL's ExceptionManager directly looks something like this:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>public class ExceptionProneClass
<br />{
<br />  public void GetSomeSqlData()
<br />  {
<br />    try
<br />    {
<br />      // do some data access
<br />    }
<br />    catch (SqlException ex)
<br />    {
<br />      // Invoke the HandleException EL method
<br />      bool rethrow = ExceptionPolicy.HandleException(ex, "Data Policy");
<br />      if (rethrow)
<br />      {
<br />        throw;
<br />      }
<br />    }
<br />    finally
<br />    {
<br />      // do cleanup
<br />    }
<br />  }
<br />}</code></pre>The wrapper class, albeit only subtly different, looks like this:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>// facade for exception management
<br />public class ExceptionManager
<br />{
<br />  const string DEFAULT_POLICY_NAME = "Standard";
<br />
<br />  public static void ProcessException(Exception ex)
<br />  {
<br />    ProcessException(ex, DEFAULT_POLICY_NAME);
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  public static void ProcessException(Exception ex, string p)
<br />  {
<br />    bool rethrow = ExceptionPolicy.HandleException(ex, p);
<br />    if (rethrow)
<br />    {
<br />      throw;
<br />    }
<br />  }
<br />
<br />  public static void ProcessException(Exception ex, ExceptionPolicyType p)
<br />  {
<br />    Type t = typeof(ExceptionPolicyType);
<br />    ProcessException(ex, Enum.GetName(t, (int)p));
<br />  }
<br />}</code></pre><br />Now our original class can be refactored to call our facade method(s) instead of referencing the EL directly. This simplifies our call to the EL ExceptionManager even more, by allowing our own class to handle rethrowing exceptions as necessary, letting us enumerate exception policy names, etc.<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>public class MyExceptionProneClass
<br />{
<br />  public void GetSomeSqlData()
<br />  {
<br />    try
<br />    {
<br />      // do some data access
<br />    }
<br />    catch (SqlException ex)
<br />    {
<br />      // Invoke our exception handler facade
<br />      ExceptionManager.ProcessException(ex, "Data Policy");
<br />    }
<br />    finally
<br />    {
<br />      // cleanup
<br />    }
<br />  }
<br />}</code></pre><br />I often follow this pattern for each of the application blocks. This might appear to undermine the time-saving advantages of the Enterprise Library, and in some cases it does. But in others - a major shift in an application's authentication and/or authorization scheme, for example - saves a costly refactor because you're too tightly coupled to the EL (or perhaps because you weren't using it at all). Granted, making a case against this isn't terribly difficult (though doing so would be substantially un-agile), but I've seen this happen at least once since the latest version of the EL was released in January.<br /><br /><a href="http://cdn.kriscargile.com/samples/msel-facades.zip">msel-facades.zip</a><br /><br />klc;

Macromedia's Flash platform has historically fallen into the realm of graphic design, used for all of those wonderfully irritating banners, <a href="http://www.homestarrunner.com/sbemail51.html" target="_blank">website intros</a> and interactive CD-ROMs. A recent project that called for using Flash as web-service front-end, however, demonstrated that Macromedia's commitment to XML and web services may very well make it a contender in the ever changing thin client game.<br /><br />One particularly compelling case for connection Flash to a web service is to provide functionality to CD-ROM applications that is traditionally available only in a server-context. Case-in-point: we were able to quickly build a multi-platform, email enabled multimedia product that could be widely distributed via the Internet, direct mail, and the like. We simply connected Flash to a set of simple XML web services and let our application server take care of the rest.<br /><a name='more'></a><br />Our ActionScript, which had no problem talking to our .NET based service layer, looked something like this:<br /><pre class="kccodeblock"><code>import mx.data.components.WebServiceConnector;
